{"title_page": "George Mathews (judge)", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = George Mathews\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = PresidingJudgeGeorgeMathews.jpg\n| alt = \n| office= Presiding Judge of the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]]\n| term_start = 1813\n| term_end = 1836\n| predecessor = New position\n| successor = [[Henry Carlton (judge)|Henry Carlton]]\n| speaker = \n| office2= Justice of the Superior Court of the [[Territory of Orleans]]\n| term_start2 = 1806\n| term_end2 = 1813\n| predecessor2 = [[Ephraim Kirby]]\n| successor2 = Court abolished\n| office3= Justice of the Superior Court of the [[Territory of Mississippi]]\n| term_start3 = 1804\n| term_end3 = 1806\n| predecessor3 = New position\n| successor3 = Court abolished\n| birth_date = September 30, 1774\n| birth_place = [[Augusta County, Virginia]]\n| death_date = November 14, 1836\n| death_place = [[St. Francisville, Louisiana]]\n|restingplace  = [[Grace Episcopal Church (St. Francisville, Louisiana)|Grace Episcopal Church]]\n| nationality = \n| spouse = Harriet Flowers\n| party = \n| relations =[[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]], father; <br>[[Mathews family]]\n| children = \n| residence = [[Butler Greenwood Plantation]]\n| alma_mater = Liberty Hall Academy [[Washington and Lee University]]\n| occupation =\n| profession = Judge\n| religion = \n| signature =\n| signature_alt =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n\n'''George Mathews Jr.''' (September 30, 1774 \u2013 November 14, 1836), was a Judge of the Superior Courts of the [[Territory of Mississippi]] and the [[Territory of Orleans]], and Presiding Judge of the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]] from 1813 until his death in 1836. His ruling in ''[[Marie Louise v. Marot]]'' was cited as precedent by dissenting [[U.S. Supreme Court Justice]] [[John McLean]] in the 1856 [[Landmark decisions in the United States|landmark]] ''[[Dred Scott v. Sandford]]'' case.\n\n==Early life==\n{{See also|Mathews family}}\nMathews was born in [[Augusta County, Virginia]], on September 30, 1774, the son of a planter and [[American Revolution|Revolutionary War]] officer, [[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]] and his wife, Polly. The elder Mathews would later serve twice as [[Governor of Georgia]].  In 1785, the elder Mathews moved himself and his whole family to [[Wilkes County, Georgia]], to land that today is in [[Oglethorpe County, Georgia|Oglethorpe County]].\n\nMathews returned to Virginia for his education at Liberty Hall Academy (which later became [[Washington and Lee University]]).  He originally set out to become a physician but was persuaded by his father to [[Reading law|study law]] under his brother, John Mathews, in [[Augusta, Georgia]].<ref name = \"Mazureau's Oration\">{{cite journal| last = Dart| first = Henry P.  | title = Mazureau's Oration on Mathews| journal = Louisiana Historical Quarterly| volume = 4| issue = 1| pages = 149| publisher = Louisiana Historical Society | location = New Orleans, Louisiana | date = September 22, 1922| url = https://archive.org/stream/louisianahistor02unkngoog/louisianahistor02unkngoog_djvu.txt   | accessdate = 2009-05-18}}</ref> He married Harriet Flowers in 1809 and they resided near [[St. Francisville, Louisiana]], at her family's [[Butler Greenwood Plantation]].<ref>National Park Service: ''Butler-Greenwood Plantation'', http://www.nps.gov/history/NR/travel/louisiana/but.htm, retrieved 27 Aug 2009.</ref>\n[[File:Butler Greenwood Plantation viewed from Old English Garden.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.0|[[Butler Greenwood Plantation]]]]\nGeorge and Harriett Mathews raised indigo, cotton, sugar cane, and corn on the [[Plantations in the American South|plantation]], shipping the crops from their own dock on Bayou Sara and extending their land holdings to include a sugar plantation in [[Lafourche Parish]] that, according to Lewis Gray's figures, placed them among the top 9% of sugar planters in the state in the 1850s.<ref>{{Citation\n| title = Butler--Greenwood Plantation\n|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]]\n| accessdate = 2009-10-10\n| url = http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/travel/louisiana/but.htm\n}}</ref>\n\n==Career on the bench==\nIn 1804 Mathews was appointed by President [[Thomas Jefferson]] to be judge of the Superior Court of the newly created [[Territory of Mississippi]].  He served for two years on that court before being appointed judge of the Superior Court for the [[Territory of Orleans]] in 1806.\n\nWhen Louisiana became a state in 1813, the territorial courts were replaced by a new Supreme Court.  Mathews was appointed by Governor [[William C.C. Claiborne]] as judge of that new high court on February 23, 1813. He served alongside Judges [[Dominic Augustin Hall]], [[Pierre Derbigny]] and [[Francois Xavier Martin]].<ref name=\"Mazureau's Oration\"/>  He reputedly learned both [[French language|French]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]] as much of the law of the State of Louisiana was rooted in the traditions of the land's previous colonial overlords and many lawyers spoke one of the two languages but not English.<ref name=\"Mazureau's Oration\"/>\n[[File:JohnMcLean.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.0|[[Us supreme court justices|US Supreme Court Justice]] [[John McLean]], who relied on Mathews' precedent for his dissent from the Court ruling in [[Dred Scott v. Sandford]] ]]\n\n=== ''Dred Scott v. Sandford'' precedent ===\nIn the early 1830s, a Louisiana family went to France with their young slave girl, Josephine Louise. When the family returned home, the slave girl's mother sued to obtain a declaration of immediate emancipation as a result of the girl being transported to a country that did not recognize the institution of slavery. The 1835 case, ''[[Marie Louise v. Marot]]'' (1836) was heard by the Louisiana state district court and appealed to the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]]. The Court held that a slave who is taken to a territory prohibitive of slavery cannot be again reduced to slavery on returning to a territory allowing of slavery. Mathews, speaking for the court, stated that \"[b]eing free for one moment...it was not in the power of her former owner to reduce her again to slavery.\"<ref name=Friedman>\"Champion of Civil Rights: Judge John Minor Wisdom\". Southern Biography Series: LSU Press, 2009, p 24. https://books.google.com/books?id=atfIkRdwQ9kC&pg=PA24&dq=%22louisiana%22+%22george+mathews%22&hl=en#v=onepage&q=%20%22george%20mathews%22&f=false Retrieved December 4, 2012.</ref>\n\n21 years later, his precedent was relied upon by [[US Supreme Court]] Justice [[John McLean (US Associate Justice)|John McLean]], who dissented from the court's [[Dred Scott v. Sandford|Dred Scott ruling]] that a slave was a piece of property that could by transported by his owner from a Southern state into a territory that forbade slavery without losing his slave status.<ref name=Friedman /> Six of 8 justices did not abide by the precedent in what has been considered the worst decision ever made by the Supreme Court.<ref name=\"Finkelman, Paul 2007\">Finkelman, Paul. [http://www.cklawreview.com/wp-content/uploads/vol82no1/Finkelman.pdf \u201cScott v. Sandford: The Court\u2019s Most Dreadful Case and How it Changed History,\u201d] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203024458/http://www.cklawreview.com/wp-content/uploads/vol82no1/Finkelman.pdf |date=2012-12-03 }} 82 Chi.-Kent L. Rev. 3 2007. Retrieved August 20, 2012.</ref>\n\n== Legacy and honors ==\nMathews died in St. Francisville on November 14, 1836 and was buried at [[Grace Episcopal Church (St. Francisville, Louisiana)|Grace Episcopal Church]].<ref>{{cite web  | title = Grace Episcopal Cemetery, St. Francisville, Louisiana  | work = Findagrave| url = http://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=gr&GSln=Mathews&GScid=2140824&GRid=35649486&| accessdate = 2009-05-18}}</ref> He left a very large fortune at his death, and his [[Will contest|will was successfully attacked]]; one of its dispositions being annulled by the Louisiana Supreme Court.<ref name=\"Wymond\">''Celebration of the Centenary of the Supreme Court of Louisiana'' (March 1, 1913), in John Wymond, Henry Plauch\u00e9 Dart, eds., ''The Louisiana Historical Quarterly'' (1922), p. 114.</ref>\n\nThe [[Louisiana Historical Association]] celebrated the Centenary of the Louisiana Supreme Court in 1922 and at that time Mathews was remembered as, \"short, rotund, placid, even-tempered, and genial, with a touch of humor and pleasantry in his intercourse with men and on the bench. His disposition crops out in his opinions which, moreover, are fine specimens of taste and learning.\"<ref>{{Cite journal  | title = Centenary of the Supreme Court| journal = Louisiana Historical Quarterly| volume = 4| issue = 1| pages = 32| date = September 22, 1922| url = https://books.google.com/?id=PkoUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA5&lpg=PA5&dq=historical+opinions+of+the+Louisiana+Supreme+Court}}</ref>\n\n[[Mathews, Louisiana]], is named in his honor.\n\n== See also ==\n* [https://archive.org/stream/discourseonlifec00watt/discourseonlifec00watt_djvu.txt A Discourse on the Life and Character of the Hon. George Mathews]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-legal}}\n{{succession box| title=[[List of justices of the Mississippi Supreme Court|Judge of the Superior Court of the Territory of Mississippi]] | before=newly created position| after=unknown| years=1804&ndash;1806}}\n{{succession box| title=[[List of justices of the Louisiana Supreme Court|Judge of the Superior Court of the Territory of Orleans]] | before=[[Ephraim Kirby]]| after=court abolished| years=1806&ndash;1813}}\n{{succession box| title=[[List of justices of the Louisiana Supreme Court|Justice of the Louisiana Supreme Court]] | before=newly created position| after=[[Henry Carlton (judge)|Henry Carlton]]| years=1813&ndash;1836<br> '''<small> Chief Justice 1821\u20131836</small>'''}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Judges of the Superior Court of the Territory of Orleans}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mathews Jr., George}}\n[[Category:1774 births]]\n[[Category:1836 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Augusta County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:People from St. Francisville, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:American planters]]\n[[Category:Chief Justices of the Louisiana Supreme Court]]\n[[Category:United States territorial judges]]\n[[Category:Freedom suits in the United States]]\n[[Category:United States slavery case law]]\n[[Category:Washington and Lee University alumni]]\n[[Category:Mathews family of Virginia and West Virginia]]\n[[Category:United States federal judges admitted to the practice of law by reading law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{Infobox state representative\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = George Mathews\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = PresidingJudgeGeorgeMathews.jpg\n| alt = \n| office= Presiding Judge of the [[Louisiana Supreme Court]]\n| term_start = 1813\n| term_end = 1836\n| predecessor = New position\n| successor = [[Henry Carlton (judge)|Henry Carlton]]\n| speaker = \n| office2= Justice of the Superior Court of the [[Territory of Orleans]]\n| term_start2 = 1806\n| term_end2 = 1813\n| predecessor2 = [[Ephraim Kirby]]\n| successor2 = Court abolished\n| office3= Justice of the Superior Court of the [[Territory of Mississippi]]\n| term_start3 = 1804\n| term_end3 = 1806\n| predecessor3 = New position\n| successor3 = Court abolished\n| birth_date = September 30, 1774\n| birth_place = [[Augusta County, Virginia]]\n| death_date = November 14, 1836\n| death_place = [[St. Francisville, Louisiana]]\n|restingplace  = [[Grace Episcopal Church (St. Francisville, Louisiana)|Grace Episcopal Church]]\n| nationality = \n| spouse = Harriet Flowers\n| party = \n| relations =[[George Mathews (Georgia)|George Mathews]], father; <br>[[Mathews family (Virginia)]]\n| children = \n| residence = [[Butler Greenwood Plantation]]\n| alma_mater = Liberty Hall Academy [[Washi